  "prompt": "Can an L2 visa holder work without EAD?",
  "response": "An L2 visa holder is the dependent of an L1 visa holder, who is an intracompany transferee in the United States. The L2 visa is granted to the spouse and unmarried children under 21 of an L1 visa holder.\n\nBy default, an L2 visa holder is not allowed to work in the United States. However, since May 2002, spouses of L1 visa holders (L2 visa holders) have been eligible to apply for an Employment Authorization Document (EAD) from the U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS). Once the EAD is approved and issued, the L2 visa holder can legally work in the United States.\n\nTo answer your question directly: No, an L2 visa holder cannot work without an EAD. They must apply for and receive an EAD before they can engage in any employment in the United States.",
